Question 1, Part F

#Shows Linearity kind of, but there is a large spread around the line
plot(Time~Ascent, data=HighPeaks)
abline(HighestPeaksMod)

The above plot shows scatter plot of Ascent and Time. There is a weak, positive linear trend we can observe here. It seems like a linear model would be appropriate to use in this case.

#Shows Zero Mean
plot(HighestPeaksMod$residuals~HighestPeaksMod$fitted.values)
abline(0,0)

The above plot shows the plot of the residuals and the fitted values from our model. The residuals seem to be randomly distbuted over the zero mean reference line. We can assume zero mean from this plot. This is another satisifed condition of using a linear model.

#Shows Independence and skewness (or lack of skewness)

hist(HighestPeaksMod$residuals)

qqnorm(HighestPeaksMod$residuals)
qqline(HighestPeaksMod$residuals)

The above histogram shows that the residuals tend to skew left. This skew wasn’t captured in the residual vs fitted value plot. Similarly, the left side of the qq plot shows more variance relative to the right side of the qq plot. This also indicates a left skew of the residuals. Depsite this, the differences do not seem to be so outlandish that we cannot assume independence. This is another satisfied condition of using a simple linear model.

Based on the above plots, a simple linear model feels appropriate to model this relationship.

Question 2, Part B

plot(log(Weight)~Length, data=Perch)                #This model does a good job of making the relationship linear
mod1=lm(log(Weight)~Length, data=Perch)
abline(mod1)

plot(Weight~log(Length), data=Perch)                #This model sucks
mod2=lm(Weight~log(Length), data=Perch)
abline(mod2)

plot(log(Weight)~log(Length), data=Perch)           #This appears to be the best model.
mod3=lm(log(Weight)~log(Length), data=Perch)
abline(mod3)

The above plot showing log(Weight)~log(Length) appears to be the best plot. This plot shows the least squares line over the scatterplot of these values. Below is a summary of the linear model.

Question 2, Part C

plot(log(Weight)~log(Length), data=Perch)
abline(mod3)

plot(mod3)

hist(mod3$residuals)

I think this relationship between log(Weight)~log(Length) is suited for modeling from a simple linear model. The least squares regression line seems to run right through the data in the first plot. The residuals seem to start off centered around the reference line, but as the fitted values increase the residuals start to deviate from this pattern. The QQ plot shows independence except for the right and left tails where they deviate from the reference line. The histogram shows that the residuals of mod3 seem to be normally distributed and without too much skew. Due to the lecture material through this point, we cannot comment on the normality of the relationship. Overall, this relationship is probably ok to modeled by a simple linear model, however, the model would be improved if we saw better evidence of Zero Mean of the residuals vs fitted values, and the if the standardized residuals didn’t increase so much in the upper right part of the QQ plot.
